Q1 Q2 Q3 Q4 Q5 Q6 Q7 Q8
Question 1: HIV cannot be contracted via casual contact. Ultimately, there must be an exchange of bodily fluids, with direct access to the bloodstream. Most commonly, HIV is transmitted via sexual behavior, and needle or syringe use. Question 2: Although generally safer than unprotected, penetrative sex, oral sex does put one at risk of contracting herpes simplex, gonorrhoea, syphillis, chlamydia, HIV, hepatitis A, B, and C, genital warts, and pubic lice. Question 3: You cannot contract HIV from inanimate objects. Again, HIV transmission only occurs when there is direct, and prolonged exposure to bodily fluids. Furthermore, once exposed to air, HIV rapidly becomes non-transmissible. Question 4: Condoms, when used consistently and correctly, do help prevent the spread of STDs, although they do not completely eliminate the risk of STD transmission. Question 5: HIV can infect anybody who is sexually active, regardless of sexual orientation, ethnicity, and occupation! As long as you are sexually active, you should consider regular testing. Question 6: There are, indeed, many sexual health clinics operated by the NHS in London. These include Dean Street Express (Soho), and the Jefferiss Wing Centre for sexual health (St. Mary\'s Hospital). Question 7: STD symptoms are not always obvious. For example, HIV symptoms may not show for several years. This is why it is important to consider regular testing. Question 8: With early virus detection, and the correct treatment, those living with HIV can expect to live a normal lifespan!
